  "issue_title": "fix: harden scroll with target-aware container resolution",
  "issue_body": "Parent: #75\n\n## Problem\n\nThe current `scroll` tool scrolls forward or backward on the active screen, but it does not resolve a specific scrollable container.\n\nThis can fail or scroll the wrong area on screens with nested lists, sheets, or panes.\n\n## Proposed behavior\n\nMake scroll target-aware where possible.\n\nThe hardened scroll flow should:\n\n- resolve scrollable containers from `ScreenContext`,\n- support current direction-only behavior as a fallback,\n- return a clear failure when no scrollable target exists,\n- record the selected scroll target in redacted debug data,\n- avoid blind repeated scrolling when the screen does not change.\n\n## User workflow\n\nWhen a user asks TouchPilot to scroll a page or list, the app should scroll the relevant container or explain that no scrollable area is available.\n\n## Local-first impact\n\nReliable local control depends on scroll behaving consistently across Android screens.\n\n## Safety and security considerations\n\nDo not use unbounded scrolling. Retry and verification must remain bounded and observable.\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- [ ] Resolver can identify scrollable nodes.\n- [ ] `scroll` can use a resolved scrollable target where possible.\n- [ ] Direction-only scroll remains compatible.\n- [ ] No-scrollable-target failure is explicit.\n- [ ] Unit tests cover single container, multiple containers, no container, and unchanged-screen behavior where practical.\n\n## Alternatives considered\n\nKeep global scroll only. Rejected because nested scroll surfaces are common on Android.\n",
